1
0:00:29,920 --> 0:00:32,520
海洋 似乎了无边际
The oceans, seemingly limitless,

2
0:00:33,070 --> 0:00:37,910
让我们充满敬畏和惊叹 有时也让我们心生畏惧
invoke in us a sense of awe and wonder and also, sometimes, fear.

3
0:00:38,680 --> 0:00:44,410
它们占据了地表的70% 然而我们却依然对其
They cover 70% of the surface of our planet and yet they are still

4
0:00:44,420 --> 0:00:46,240
知之甚少
the least explored.

5
0:00:47,900 --> 0:00:51,980
隐藏在波涛之下 就在我脚下的水里
Hidden beneath the waves, right beneath my feet,

6
0:00:51,980 --> 0:00:55,210
生活着我们想象不到的生物
there are creatures beyond our imagination.

7
0:01:10,520 --> 0:01:14,360
在新技术的帮助下 我们能够进入崭新的世界
With revolutionary technology, we can enter new worlds...

8
0:01:20,480 --> 0:01:24,000
以前人不可能完成的方式
..and shine a light on behaviours in ways that were impossible

9
0:01:24,000 --> 0:01:25,700
探究海洋生物的行为
just a generation ago.

10
0:01:29,480 --> 0:01:32,440
我们也意识到一个不安的现实
We've also recognised an uncomfortable fact...

11
0:01:32,440 --> 0:01:35,080
我们的海洋正受到健康威胁
The health of our oceans is under threat.

12
0:01:35,080 --> 0:01:39,300
它正以人类历史上前所未有的速度改变着
They are changing at a faster rate than ever before in human history.

13
0:01:45,800 --> 0:01:50,680
趁现在来揭示海面下发生的一切
Never has there been a more crucial time to reveal what is going on

14
0:01:50,680 --> 0:01:52,880
比任何时候都更为重要
beneath the surface of the seas.

15
0:02:07,760 --> 0:02:10,060
在第一集中
In this first episode,

16
0:02:11,880 --> 0:02:14,480
我们将抵达地球的各个海域
we will journey across the globe

17
0:02:14,480 --> 0:02:17,160
从温暖的热带水域
from the warm waters of the Tropics

18
0:02:19,760 --> 0:02:22,560
一路到最寒冷的极地水域
to the coldest around the poles...

19
0:02:26,880 --> 0:02:31,540
让我们对海面下的生命有一个全新的认识
..to bring us a new understanding of life beneath the waves.

20
0:02:38,280 --> 0:02:41,210
这里是蓝色星球Ⅱ
This is Blue Planet II.

21
0:03:39,800 --> 0:03:44,520
许多生物潜藏在海面之下
The surface of the ocean conceals many creatures that live beneath.

22
0:03:56,840 --> 0:03:59,640
但也有例外
But not all.

23
0:04:02,320 --> 0:04:03,960
宽吻海豚
Bottlenose dolphins.

24
0:04:07,440 --> 0:04:09,880
它们极其聪明
They are extremely intelligent.

25
0:04:20,240 --> 0:04:23,040
伴随智慧而来的是顽皮
And with this intelligence comes playfulness.

26
0:04:30,680 --> 0:04:35,760
它们喜欢冲浪 而且据我们所知
They surf and, as far as we can tell,

27
0:04:35,760 --> 0:04:38,480
它们这样做完全是为了好玩
they do so for the sheer joy of it.

28
0:05:06,560 --> 0:05:11,000
但要想真正了解他们的性情
But to properly appreciate their true character,

29
0:05:11,000 --> 0:05:15,000
你必须跟着他们 进入它们的世界
you have to travel with them into their world.

30
0:05:28,280 --> 0:05:30,480
一群宽吻海豚
A pod of bottlenose dolphins

31
0:05:30,480 --> 0:05:33,200
正拜访一处位于红海的珊瑚礁
is visiting a coral reef in the Red Sea.

32
0:05:35,600 --> 0:05:39,080
对小海豚来说 学习的时候到了
For the youngsters, there are things to be learned here.

33
0:05:48,400 --> 0:05:53,240
成年海豚领着一只小海豚来到一个灌木形状的珊瑚旁
The adults lead a calf to a particular bush-like coral

34
0:05:53,240 --> 0:05:55,880
这是柳珊瑚
called a gorgonian.

35
0:06:09,120 --> 0:06:12,520
在这里 成年海豚做出了一个奇怪的举动
And here the adults behave rather strangely.

36
0:06:19,000 --> 0:06:22,760
他们故意从珊瑚上擦过
They deliberately rub themselves through the fronds.

37
0:06:35,480 --> 0:06:38,920
小家伙似乎不愿意这样做
Their calf seems reluctant to do so.

38
0:06:51,280 --> 0:06:52,840
但看见长辈们都这样做
By watching his elders,

39
0:06:52,840 --> 0:06:56,400
他也许意识到了自己也必须这样做
he may be realising that this is something he ought to do.

40
0:07:03,440 --> 0:07:05,440
实际上 柳珊瑚表面
Gorgonian fronds, in fact,

41
0:07:05,440 --> 0:07:09,480
覆盖着一层粘液
are covered with a mucus that can have anti-inflammatory

42
0:07:09,480 --> 0:07:12,120
具有消炎抗菌的功效
and antimicrobial properties.

43
0:07:16,720 --> 0:07:19,200
所以成年海豚这样做也许是为了
So maybe the adult dolphins are doing this

44
0:07:19,200 --> 0:07:21,840
防止皮肤感染
to protect themselves from infection.

45
0:07:31,840 --> 0:07:36,640
海豚关于珊瑚礁的丰富知识
The dolphins' intimate knowledge of the reef

46
0:07:36,640 --> 0:07:40,520
也启发我们在这里寻找新药物
is spurring us to search for new medicines here, too.

47
0:07:50,480 --> 0:07:56,040
热带珊瑚礁只占海床总面积的0.1%
Tropical coral reefs occupy only a tenth of 1% of the ocean floor.

48
0:07:59,000 --> 0:08:03,300
但这片有着全年稳定条件的温暖浅水区
But their shallow warm waters and stable year-round conditions

49
0:08:03,320 --> 0:08:06,960
却供养着海洋里最丰富多样的
support some of the most crowded and varied communities

50
0:08:06,960 --> 0:08:09,680
生物群落
to be found anywhere in the oceans.

51
0:08:13,040 --> 0:08:16,640
每一个物种都有待研究
And there are new discoveries to be made on every one of them.

52
0:08:37,400 --> 0:08:42,040
在澳大利亚的大堡礁 生活着一种鱼
One creature on Australia's Great Barrier Reef is challenging our

53
0:08:42,040 --> 0:08:46,080
它颠覆了我们对鱼智慧的认识
understanding of fish intelligence.

54
0:08:46,080 --> 0:08:48,160
一只猪齿鱼
A tuskfish.

55
0:08:48,160 --> 0:08:50,160
你很快就会明白它名字的由来
And you can see why it gets its name.

56
0:08:55,880 --> 0:08:59,160
他做的事很少有人相信鱼能做到
He does something few would have believed a fish could do.

57
0:09:06,640 --> 0:09:10,000
每天早晨他游到珊瑚礁边缘
Every morning he travels to the edge of the reef.

58
0:09:24,720 --> 0:09:28,560
他在珊瑚残骸和沙子中
He is searching for something special to eat amongst the coral

59
0:09:28,560 --> 0:09:29,360
寻找一种特殊的食物
rubble and sand.

60
0:09:41,120 --> 0:09:42,040
找到了一个
Here is one.

61
0:09:44,400 --> 0:09:45,400
一只小蛤蜊
A small clam.

62
0:09:53,760 --> 0:09:56,360
但怎样才能把它打开 吃到里面的肉呢
But how to crack it open and get to the meat?

63
0:10:08,200 --> 0:10:12,240
他把它一路带回自己的私人厨房
He takes it all the way back to his special kitchen.

64
0:10:21,370 --> 0:10:23,560
一个碗状珊瑚
A bowl-shaped coral

65
0:10:23,570 --> 0:10:28,080
里面有处可以用于故技重施的凸起
 that has a particular bump on the inside that he always uses.

66
0:10:45,260 --> 0:10:49,040
没有手的话这将是件很困难的事
It's not easy if you have no hands.

67
0:10:57,240 --> 0:11:00,520
喔 又没中
Whoops, there he goes again.

68
0:11:05,240 --> 0:11:07,480
但他有极大的决心
But he's got great determination...

69
0:11:13,880 --> 0:11:15,600
和惊人的准确性
..and surprising accuracy.

70
0:11:35,600 --> 0:11:36,520
终于
At last!

71
0:11:39,720 --> 0:11:42,640
所以这是一只会使用工具的鱼
So here is a fish that uses tools.

72
0:11:44,880 --> 0:11:49,160
有些鱼比你想象的聪明得多
Some fish are much cleverer than you might suppose.

73
0:12:06,200 --> 0:12:08,570
热带珊瑚礁里密集的生物群落
The density of the animals on tropical reefs

74
0:12:08,910 --> 0:12:12,720
使得竞争不可避免而异常激烈
makes competition inevitable and extreme.

75
0:12:13,960 --> 0:12:16,960
不只是对于那些居住在珊瑚礁里的生物
Not only for those that live within the reefs...

76
0:12:18,400 --> 0:12:20,600
对在上面飞着的鸟儿也是一样
..but for the birds that fly above them.

77
0:12:24,320 --> 0:12:26,120
在旱季
During the dry season,

78
0:12:26,120 --> 0:12:30,760
超过五十万只乌燕鸥飞到这个偏远的
over half a million terns crowd onto this remote atoll

79
0:12:30,760 --> 0:12:32,480
印度洋环礁岛上
in the Indian Ocean.

80
0:12:39,920 --> 0:12:42,800
它们的雏鸟还披着未长成的黑色绒羽
Their chicks are still in their dark juvenile plumage.

81
0:12:48,120 --> 0:12:49,440
它们年龄大小各不相同
They vary in age.

82
0:12:58,200 --> 0:13:01,240
当大些的飞向天空时
Whilst the more advanced chicks take to the air..

83
0:13:08,900 --> 0:13:11,000
小点的还飞不起来
..others aren't quite ready yet.

84
0:13:31,800 --> 0:13:36,800
岛屿中心浅浅的环礁湖成为了
Those just starting to learn to fly use the shallow lagoon that occupies

85
0:13:36,800 --> 0:13:39,760
这些幼鸟的飞行训练场
the centre of the atoll as their training ground.

86
0:13:42,320 --> 0:13:45,760
对部分幼鸟而言 长时间停留在空中还很困难
It's difficult for some of them to stay aloft for long.

87
0:14:09,520 --> 0:14:11,520
珍鲹
Giant trevally.

88
0:14:24,080 --> 0:14:28,240
它们通常单独捕食
Usually they are solitary hunters.

89
0:14:28,240 --> 0:14:32,040
但在天降美食的诱惑下 会有50只左右的珍鲹
But about 50 of them have come here from neighbouring reefs,

90
0:14:32,040 --> 0:14:35,120
从附近的珊瑚礁赶来赴宴
attracted by this abundance of potential prey.

91
0:14:43,520 --> 0:14:46,690
幼鸟尽量不在水面做任何停留
The fledglings stay out of the water if they can.

92
0:14:48,560 --> 0:14:50,320
连喝水的时候也不落下来
They even drink on the wing.

93
0:15:08,400 --> 0:15:11,680
如果珍鲹现在要抓到它们
If the trevally are to catch one now,

94
0:15:11,680 --> 0:15:13,680
就必须加大筹码
they have to up their game.

95
0:15:23,440 --> 0:15:26,720
所以一只鱼 能够不可思议地
So there was a fish here that, amazingly,

96
0:15:26,720 --> 0:15:30,960
计算出空气的流速
has a brain capable of calculating the airspeed,

97
0:15:30,960 --> 0:15:34,000
鸟的飞行高度和轨迹
altitude and trajectory of a bird.

98
0:16:05,220 --> 0:16:09,100
幼鸟们飞向天空
The time comes when every fledgling has to take to the air

99
0:16:09,120 --> 0:16:12,130
独立觅食的时候到了
and collect food for itself.

100
0:16:35,360 --> 0:16:38,160
它们的父母把它们领到训练场
Their parents lead them to the training grounds.

101
0:18:13,440 --> 0:18:16,000
要想活下去
If they are to survive,

102
0:18:16,000 --> 0:18:17,480
它们必须尽快学会飞翔
they must learn quickly.

103
0:18:26,080 --> 0:18:29,320
在环礁湖上训练一个月后
After a month of practising over the lagoon,

104
0:18:29,320 --> 0:18:34,780
幼鸟们便开始离开 踏上翻洋过海的征程
the youngsters start to leave and take their chances over the open sea.

105
0:18:41,480 --> 0:18:46,960
海洋中的水占地球总水量的97%
The oceans hold 97% of all the water in the world.

106
0:18:49,800 --> 0:18:54,320
当太阳照到水面 水分蒸发
As the sun warms the surface, water evaporates.

107
0:18:54,320 --> 0:18:58,400
蒸气升腾到空中
It vaporises into the sky until it cools and condenses

108
0:18:58,400 --> 0:19:01,600
直到遇冷凝结成云
into towering clouds.

109
0:19:02,800 --> 0:19:06,600
它们产生巨大的风暴
And they generate huge storms.

110
0:19:10,000 --> 0:19:14,920
地球自转使这些气旋向南北分散
The spin of the Earth deflects these storms north and south

111
0:19:14,920 --> 0:19:16,960
进入高纬地区
into cooler latitudes.

112
0:19:25,520 --> 0:19:27,800
它们经过海面时
As they travel across the sea,

113
0:19:27,800 --> 0:19:31,600
风暴掀起万丈狂澜
storm-driven winds create huge swells.

114
0:19:43,960 --> 0:19:46,140
当波澜到达浅水区
When the swells reach shallower water,

115
0:19:46,540 --> 0:19:49,960
就会变成滔天巨浪
they rise into gigantic waves.

116
0:20:07,440 --> 0:20:11,560
一次大风暴释放的能量
In it lifetime, a large storm can release energy

117
0:20:11,560 --> 0:20:16,100
相当于一万颗核弹的威力
that is the equivalent of 10,000 nuclear bombs.

118
0:20:40,520 --> 0:20:43,520
这些是季节性海域
These are the seasonal seas.

119
0:20:46,320 --> 0:20:51,180
当春暖人间时 它们就会爆发出蓬勃的生命力
And when they warm in spring, they can suddenly explode with life.

120
0:21:06,120 --> 0:21:12,610
大量的蝠鲼聚集在墨西哥的科斯特湾
Mobula rays have gathered in Mexico's Sea of Cortez in vast numbers.

121
0:21:19,520 --> 0:21:20,520
它们为什么跃出水面
Why do they leap?

122
0:21:23,680 --> 0:21:25,600
是要告诉同类自己在这吗
Is it to tell others that they are here?

123
0:21:29,400 --> 0:21:30,400
没有人知道
No-one knows.

124
0:21:34,400 --> 0:21:36,960
他们大多在晚上觅食
They feed mostly at night,

125
0:21:36,960 --> 0:21:41,480
因为那时 大量的浮游生物会从海底涌上来
for that is when vast swarms of plankton rise from the depths.

126
0:21:47,880 --> 0:21:50,800
海水的扰动
The disturbance in the water stimulates many

127
0:21:50,800 --> 0:21:53,840
使得许多浮游生物发出微光
of the planktonic creatures to luminesce.

128
0:21:55,760 --> 0:22:00,320
现在我们可以借助新的摄影技术 拍到这些微光
Only now do we have the technology to record their faint glow.

129
0:22:09,600 --> 0:22:12,120
觅食的蝠鲼在这些微光间穿梭
The feasting rays swim through them,

130
0:22:12,120 --> 0:22:16,560
演绎一支生与死的芭蕾
creating an extraordinary ballet of life and death.

131
0:23:04,760 --> 0:23:09,640
这些海域的富饶得益于丰富的微生植物
The richness of these waters is based on microscopic plants -

132
0:23:09,640 --> 0:23:15,280
浮游植物 无比繁盛的它们造福了整个生物圈
phytoplankton - which bloom on such a massive scale they benefit us all.

133
0:23:18,840 --> 0:23:22,480
它们 连同海草和海藻
They, together with seaweeds and sea grasses,

134
0:23:22,480 --> 0:23:27,800
制造的氧气足以胜过于陆地上所有森林和草场的总和
produce as much oxygen as all the forests and grassy plains on land.

135
0:23:39,480 --> 0:23:43,320
每年春天 新西兰沿岸季节性的富足
Every spring, off New Zealand, the seasonal bounty

136
0:23:43,320 --> 0:23:45,560
引来了难得的访客
draws in rare visitors.

137
0:23:54,000 --> 0:23:55,660
伪虎鲸
False killer whales.

138
0:23:59,560 --> 0:24:01,800
它们和虎鲸有亲缘关系
They are relatives of the orca,

139
0:24:01,800 --> 0:24:04,480
身长六米 体重超过一吨
six metres long and weighing over a tonne.

140
0:24:13,690 --> 0:24:16,840
它们似乎正在搜寻海豚
They appear to be searching for dolphins.

141
0:24:20,130 --> 0:24:23,140
沿岸的水域有很多
And there are many in these coastal waters.

142
0:24:32,700 --> 0:24:35,460
这里 一群宽吻海豚在一起游动
Here, bottlenose dolphins stick together,

143
0:24:35,520 --> 0:24:38,760
不断地用超声波相互交流
constantly chattering with whistles and clicks.

144
0:24:48,360 --> 0:24:50,880
这种声音在水下能传到几英里外的地方
Such a din carries for miles underwater.

145
0:24:57,720 --> 0:24:59,600
伪虎鲸侦查到了它们
The false killers have detected them.

146
0:25:23,480 --> 0:25:26,720
十个一群 这些杀手朝他们围拢过来
Travelling at ten knots, the killers quickly close in on them.

147
0:25:45,040 --> 0:25:48,680
但突然 神奇的事情发生了
But then, something truly extraordinary happens.

148
0:25:54,960 --> 0:26:00,640
海豚转过身来 就像问候这些伪虎鲸一样
The dolphins turn, as if to greet their pursuers.

149
0:26:08,360 --> 0:26:10,600
它们似乎改变了方向
They seem to change their course.

150
0:26:12,840 --> 0:26:15,840
他们是否有可能是在尝试交流呢
Could it be that they are attempting to communicate?

151
0:26:25,640 --> 0:26:29,880
研究它们这一行为的科学家现在认为
Scientists studying this annual encounter now think that

152
0:26:29,880 --> 0:26:32,360
它们个体之间可能相互认识
individuals may recognise one another.

153
0:26:36,000 --> 0:26:37,440
出乎意料地
Almost unbelievably,

154
0:26:37,440 --> 0:26:41,880
两个不同的物种居然是老相识
it seems that these different species appear to be old friends.

155
0:26:49,450 --> 0:26:54,940
他们一起组成一支大军 数量达一千之多
Together they are gathering as one unified army, up to 1,000-strong.

156
0:27:03,040 --> 0:27:06,800
这个巨大的捕猎队伍现在要去收获
This formidable hunting party now harvests the riches

157
0:27:06,800 --> 0:27:09,560
伴随新西兰夏季而来的自然馈赠
that come with New Zealand's summer.

158
0:27:32,080 --> 0:27:34,800
在中纬度地区
All across the higher latitudes,

159
0:27:34,800 --> 0:27:38,120
季节性海域在夏日的阳光下焕发出蓬勃生机
seasonal seas flourish under the summer sun.

160
0:27:41,680 --> 0:27:42,920
在阿拉斯加
Here in Alaska,

161
0:27:42,920 --> 0:27:47,480
海獭在海底森林的树冠上晒太阳
sea otters lounge in the canopy of great submarine forests.

162
0:27:54,760 --> 0:28:01,480
巨藻 世界上最大的藻类 是各种海洋生物的家
Giant kelp, the biggest seaweed of all, is home to all kinds of life.

163
0:28:03,120 --> 0:28:07,280
在这片森林的地面上 浑身带刺的海胆啃食着巨藻
On the forest floor, spiny sea urchins munch through the kelp.

164
0:28:09,840 --> 0:28:14,080
另一处 是不断进食的海参
Elsewhere, there are continuously hungry sea cucumbers.

165
0:28:17,160 --> 0:28:22,400
在下面缠绕的水草中间 是伪装自己的叶海马
And in the tangled undergrowth, wonderfully camouflaged sea dragons.

166
0:28:33,000 --> 0:28:37,840
在日本北部的海底森林
In the underwater forests of northern Japan,

167
0:28:37,840 --> 0:28:39,640
一艘沉船上的居民们
the residents of the sunken wreck

168
0:28:39,640 --> 0:28:41,960
正等待着水温上升到
are waiting for the summer temperatures

169
0:28:41,960 --> 0:28:44,600
十六摄氏度
to reach 16 Celsius.

170
0:28:56,760 --> 0:28:59,960
对于一些居民来说 那意味着交配的时间到了
That, for some, is the time for mating.

171
0:29:14,250 --> 0:29:17,960
金黄突额隆头鱼 当地叫它Kobudai
A kind of giant wrasse called a Kobudai.

172
0:29:24,760 --> 0:29:25,760
这是一只雄性
This is a male.

173
0:29:31,080 --> 0:29:34,400
以雌鱼的眼光来看 他非常英俊
And in female terms, he is particularly handsome.

174
0:29:42,480 --> 0:29:46,720
他身长一米 体重十五公斤
He's a metre long and weighs 15 kilos.

175
0:29:49,800 --> 0:29:52,640
比身边的雌鱼大很多
Much larger than the diminutive female.

176
0:29:56,770 --> 0:29:58,880
他准备好交配了
And he is ready to breed.

177
0:30:02,400 --> 0:30:05,240
他试图和她交配
He attempts to mate with her -

178
0:30:05,240 --> 0:30:09,530
还有住在他领地里的另外十多只雌鱼
and with any of the other dozen or so females that live in his territory

179
0:30:11,280 --> 0:30:12,960
只要他逮着机会
whenever he gets the chance.

180
0:30:27,720 --> 0:30:30,600
但年约十岁的雌性
But females from around ten years old

181
0:30:30,600 --> 0:30:33,400
却不为所动
take little notice of his advances.

182
0:31:01,480 --> 0:31:06,680
这是因为当雌鱼的体型达到一定程度
This is because when any large female reaches a critical body size,

183
0:31:06,680 --> 0:31:09,760
就会经历身体上的巨大转变
she could begin a dramatic transformation.

184
0:31:27,440 --> 0:31:29,320
几个月内
Over just a few months,

185
0:31:29,320 --> 0:31:33,240
她体内的某些酶停止工作
particular enzymes inside her body cease to work.

186
0:31:35,600 --> 0:31:38,800
雄性荷尔蒙开始分散到全身的各个部位
And male hormones started to circulate.

187
0:31:43,240 --> 0:31:46,160
一段时间后
As time passes,

188
0:31:46,160 --> 0:31:50,000
她的头部隆起 下巴变长
her head expands and her chin gets longer.

189
0:31:53,240 --> 0:31:56,960
她变成了他
A she has changed into a he.

190
0:32:06,880 --> 0:32:09,720
性情也随之大变
And with this comes a change in temperament.

191
0:32:16,160 --> 0:32:18,920
以前统领这里的雄鱼
The old male who ruled all the females here.

192
0:32:21,440 --> 0:32:23,720
受到了挑战
..is challenged to a face-off.

193
0:32:30,600 --> 0:32:35,480
头越大 越能吓住对手
The more bulbous the head, the more it intimidates an opponent.

194
0:33:02,440 --> 0:33:05,240
这片领地有了新主人
The territory has a new ruler.

195
0:33:17,600 --> 0:33:21,480
只有体型最大的雌鱼才会经历这种转变
Only the largest females transform themselves in this way.

196
0:33:27,400 --> 0:33:31,200
这种转变使得它们获得更多的交配机会
But the change enables them to have more mates,

197
0:33:31,200 --> 0:33:35,000
所以就会有更多的后代携带它们的优良基因
so they will have many more offspring carrying their genes.

198
0:33:41,200 --> 0:33:43,560
但新主人也不能掉以轻心
But a new male can't afford to be complacent.

199
0:33:46,080 --> 0:33:50,640
因为在每一只雌性Kobudai的身体里
Inside the body of every Kobudai female,

200
0:33:50,640 --> 0:33:53,120
都蛰伏着一个新的雄性
there is a new male in waiting.

201
0:34:12,850 --> 0:34:17,460
越往两极 海水的温度越低
The closer we travel towards poles, the colder the seas become.

202
0:34:21,360 --> 0:34:22,880
海面开始出现冰山
Icebergs appear,

203
0:34:22,880 --> 0:34:25,040
从冰川上崩落到海里的
huge slabs that have broken away

204
0:34:25,040 --> 0:34:28,040
巨大冰块
from glaciers that are sliding into the sea.

205
0:34:29,680 --> 0:34:32,920
然后海面开始结冰
And then the surface starts to freeze.

206
0:34:43,520 --> 0:34:46,760
当极光在空中舞蹈
While the lights of the aurora play above,

207
0:34:46,760 --> 0:34:48,960
即使在冬季最冷的时候
even in the depths of midwinter,

208
0:34:48,960 --> 0:34:52,600
北极圈内的某些地方
there are a few places well north of the Arctic Circle

209
0:34:52,600 --> 0:34:54,480
海面依然没有封冻
that are still open.

210
0:35:05,440 --> 0:35:10,840
一股巨大的洋流使得挪威北部的峡湾没有结冰
The fjords of northern Norway remain ice-free because a giant current,

211
0:35:10,840 --> 0:35:11,890
墨西哥湾暖流
the Gulf Stream,

212
0:35:11,890 --> 0:35:16,800
从南部的加勒比海带来热量
flows up here from the south, bringing warmth all the way from the Caribbean.

213
0:35:21,120 --> 0:35:25,840
每年冬天 数以亿计的鲱鱼来这里越冬
And every winter, billions of herring come here for shelter.

214
0:35:29,800 --> 0:35:31,480
紧随其后的是
And following them...

215
0:35:34,200 --> 0:35:35,120
虎鲸
..orca.

216
0:35:47,280 --> 0:35:49,200
有1000只之多
There are up to 1,000 of them.

217
0:35:51,520 --> 0:35:55,320
这也许是世界上规模最大的虎鲸集体活动
It's possibly the greatest gathering of orca on the planet.

218
0:36:05,400 --> 0:36:07,520
虽然鲱鱼很多
The herring may be plentiful,

219
0:36:07,520 --> 0:36:11,920
但要想在广阔的峡湾地带抓住它们可不容易
but in these widening fjords they're not always easy to track down.

220
0:36:17,160 --> 0:36:21,800
但这些虎鲸可是专业的捕鱼能手
These particular orca, however, are fish-hunting specialists.

221
0:36:31,000 --> 0:36:32,600
它们团结组队
They work as a team,

222
0:36:32,600 --> 0:36:36,640
相互之间通过声音交流协作
coordinating their approach by calling loudly to one another.

223
0:36:41,970 --> 0:36:45,560
把鲱鱼群赶得越来越密
They herd the herring into tighter and tighter shoals.

224
0:37:00,660 --> 0:37:04,440
然后游到它们下方 把它们赶向水面
They swim below them, trapping them against the surface of the sea.

225
0:37:13,640 --> 0:37:16,800
现在虎鲸使出了它们的杀手锏
And now the orca deploy their special weapon.

226
0:37:22,640 --> 0:37:28,250
他们振尾一甩 冲击波将鲱鱼击昏
They beat their tails with such force that the shockwaves stun the herring.

227
0:37:31,290 --> 0:37:35,000
然后它们不费吹灰之力地将毫无知觉的鲱鱼吃进肚里
And then the senseless victims are easily collected.

228
0:38:09,130 --> 0:38:13,080
水下巨大的动静也引来了其他的捕食者
But all this underwater noise attracts others.

229
0:38:20,840 --> 0:38:22,880
座头鲸
Humpback whales.

230
0:38:24,320 --> 0:38:26,280
他们也加入进来
They move in on the action.

231
0:38:35,280 --> 0:38:39,760
它们从下方靠拢鱼群 然后猛冲上来
They approach the shoal from beneath and then lunge upwards...

232
0:38:45,400 --> 0:38:49,240
一口能吞下100公斤的鲱鱼
...gathering up to 100 kilos of herring in a single mouthful.

233
0:39:08,640 --> 0:39:12,130
座头鲸相对算是此地的新住户
The humpbacks are comparative newcomers.

234
0:39:12,210 --> 0:39:15,480
它们是近十年才开始来这里的
They only started coming here within the last decade.

235
0:39:26,640 --> 0:39:29,500
但这些鲱鱼数量如此庞大
But these policies are so rich

236
0:39:29,530 --> 0:39:32,600
似乎没有出现争抢食物的局面
that there appears to be enough food for everyone.

237
0:39:54,760 --> 0:39:59,080
但是 要是没有这支洋流
Nonetheless, few, if any,of these riches would be here

238
0:39:59,080 --> 0:40:02,200
这里就不会有这种丰饶和富足
 were it not for the Gulf Stream.

239
0:40:10,760 --> 0:40:15,320
事实上 洋流对地球的健康至关重要
Ocean currents, in fact, are crucial to the wellbeing of our planet.

240
0:40:20,360 --> 0:40:23,320
它们把太阳的热量
They distribute the sun's heat towards the poles

241
0:40:23,320 --> 0:40:27,640
从赤道一路带到两极
all the way from the Equator,

242
0:40:27,640 --> 0:40:31,640
使得几乎地球上的各个角落都适合生物的生存
maintaining a climate favourable for life almost everywhere.

243
0:40:38,640 --> 0:40:42,000
调节气候 制造氧气
From creating the weather to producing oxygen,

244
0:40:42,000 --> 0:40:44,360
海洋保持着我们这颗星球的健康
the seas keep our world healthy.

245
0:40:53,800 --> 0:40:56,340
但一些令人担忧的迹象表明 
But there are now worrying signs that

246
0:40:56,360 --> 0:41:00,580
千年来一直保持着相对稳定的海洋环境
conditions in the oceans that have remained relatively stable for millennia

247
0:41:01,100 --> 0:41:02,760
正在发生剧烈的改变
are changing rapidly.

248
0:41:05,000 --> 0:41:08,120
没有什么地方比北极体现得更明显
Nowhere is this more evident than in the Arctic.

249
0:41:10,560 --> 0:41:12,680
过去的30年里
Here in the past 30 years,

250
0:41:12,680 --> 0:41:16,920
北极夏季的冰川总量减少了40%
the extent of the ice in summer has been reduced by 40%.

251
0:41:18,240 --> 0:41:23,180
这种急剧变暖 极可能是人类活动的结果
This sudden warming, most likely a consequence of human activity,

252
0:41:23,370 --> 0:41:26,960
这正对野生动物造成深远影响
is having a profound impact on its wildlife.

253
0:41:34,040 --> 0:41:37,640
海象就是最大的受害者之一
Walruses are among those that are seriously affected.

254
0:41:47,370 --> 0:41:51,680
每个成年母亲都需要给她80公斤的宝宝
Every adult female needs to find a safe place

255
0:41:51,680 --> 0:41:54,560
找一个休憩的场所
where her 80-kilo pup can rest.

256
0:41:57,400 --> 0:42:01,840
他们原地盘上的海冰大多都在消融
The sea ice is retreating from much of the walruses' traditional range

257
0:42:01,840 --> 0:42:04,540
所以现在他们只能躺在干燥的地面上
so they now have to haul out on dry land.

258
0:42:10,140 --> 0:42:13,640
但一百多只好斗的母亲 一些体重接近一吨
But a herd of hundreds of quarrelsome mothers -

259
0:42:13,640 --> 0:42:17,400
挤在一起 可不是理想的的育儿场所
some weighing almost a tonne - is not an ideal nursery.

260
0:42:26,860 --> 0:42:30,480
海象在陆地上待在一起是很明智的
Walruses on land stick together for good reason.

261
0:42:32,920 --> 0:42:34,120
北极熊
Polar bears.

262
0:42:38,840 --> 0:42:42,080
一只成年雄海象体型巨大
A full-grown male walrus is gigantic -

263
0:42:42,080 --> 0:42:44,680
北极熊也不敢轻举妄动
too big for even a polar bear to tackle.

264
0:42:46,760 --> 0:42:49,960
她要找的是海象宝宝
So the bear is looking for a walrus baby.

265
0:42:56,400 --> 0:42:59,360
海象们嗅到北极熊的气味
The scent of the bear spreads alarm to the colony.

266
0:43:06,680 --> 0:43:09,080
纷纷退回海里
The walruses retreat into the sea.

267
0:43:27,480 --> 0:43:30,400
北极熊知道在水下抓不到它们
The bear knows it won't be able to catch them there.

268
0:43:40,760 --> 0:43:43,120
但她也有孩子要喂养
But she, too, has young ones to feed.

269
0:43:50,920 --> 0:43:52,840
一个母亲又能如何呢
What is a mother to do?

270
0:44:03,880 --> 0:44:08,200
一个海象母亲需要找个地方 让孩子休息
A mother walrus still needs to find a place where her young can rest.

271
0:44:15,880 --> 0:44:17,920
一块正在融化的冰山就很好
A melting iceberg might do.

272
0:44:19,560 --> 0:44:22,400
但已经有人捷足先登了
But she is not the first to find this one.

273
0:44:30,120 --> 0:44:32,520
合适的位置已经被占了
Suitable places are already taken.

274
0:45:06,240 --> 0:45:08,760
其他的母亲不愿意分享
Other mothers don't want to share.

275
0:45:13,880 --> 0:45:17,040
她们也需要地方来保护她们的孩子
They, too, need a patch of ice where they can protect their young.

276
0:45:23,760 --> 0:45:27,840
绝望的母亲只能强取豪夺
A desperate mother has no choice but to barge her way in.

277
0:45:51,280 --> 0:45:54,960
所以这下好了 都没得地方休息了
So this time, everyone loses.

278
0:46:19,440 --> 0:46:22,810
要在这些正在消融的冰岸上找个合适的休憩之所
Finding the right place on these melting shores

279
0:46:22,890 --> 0:46:25,250
越来越困难
gets harder and harder.

280
0:47:00,080 --> 0:47:02,850
共同解决这些问题
Solving these problems together

281
0:47:02,890 --> 0:47:08,760
能够帮助母子双方 在余生里
helps create a bond so strong that the mother will stay in contact with her young

282
0:47:08,760 --> 0:47:10,920
建起一种强大的纽带
for the rest of her life.

283
0:47:22,200 --> 0:47:25,360
但谁又知道它们的未来会怎样呢
But who knows now what their future will be?

284
0:47:39,650 --> 0:47:42,880
随着我们对海洋生物
As we understand more about the complexity

285
0:47:42,880 --> 0:47:46,720
的了解加深
of the lives of sea creatures,

286
0:47:46,720 --> 0:47:52,680
我们开始珍惜它们脆弱的家园
so we begin to appreciate the fragility of their home,

287
0:47:52,680 --> 0:47:54,450
我们的蓝色星球
our blue planet.

288
0:48:30,240 --> 0:48:33,440
蓝色星球II拍摄历时四年
Blue Planet II has been four years in the making.

289
0:48:36,560 --> 0:48:39,080
拍摄足迹遍布四大洋
The teams have explored every ocean,

290
0:48:39,080 --> 0:48:43,600
记录下很多不为人知的非凡故事 其中很多都是科学上的新发现
discovering extraordinary untold stories, many new to science.

291
0:48:50,800 --> 0:48:57,080
让我们对海面下的生命有新的认识和了解
Bringing a new understanding of life beneath the waves.

292
0:49:05,160 --> 0:49:09,690
最新的潜水科技 能够不产生气泡和噪音 
The latest diving technology, producing no bubbles or noise,

293
0:49:09,700 --> 0:49:13,640
使我们的摄影队伍能够长时间近距离地进行拍摄
has allowed our teams longer and closer encounters.

294
0:49:20,400 --> 0:49:23,840
为了探索深海
To explore our final frontier, the deep,

295
0:49:23,840 --> 0:49:27,080
我们在潜水器里呆了1000个小时
we've spent 1,000 hours in submersibles

296
0:49:27,080 --> 0:49:29,960
那是超过半英里深的水下
over half a mile below the surface.

297
0:49:34,000 --> 0:49:37,480
创新的摄影技术帮助我们
Innovative new camera technology makes it possible

298
0:49:37,480 --> 0:49:40,280
拍到以前从未拍到过的景象
to film moments never seen before.

299
0:49:42,560 --> 0:49:47,840
极度低光摄像机能捕捉到肉眼看不见的神奇景象
Lowlight cameras capture magical events almost invisible to the naked eye.

300
0:49:59,000 --> 0:50:02,320
探测摄像头给了我们
Probe cameras give a completely fresh perspective

301
0:50:02,320 --> 0:50:04,840
观察微小生物的全新视角
into the lives of tiny creatures...

302
0:50:04,840 --> 0:50:07,080
来了 它来了
Here it comes, here it comes.

303
0:50:07,080 --> 0:50:11,960
吸盘摄像机能够让我们以鲸的视野看海洋
..while suction cameras take us on a giant's-eye view of the ocean.

304
0:50:19,320 --> 0:50:23,160
但在海上工作世事难料 也很危险
But the sea is an unpredictable and dangerous place to work.

305
0:50:28,240 --> 0:50:32,400
特别是所谓的 南非狂野海岸
Nowhere more so than the so-called wild coast of South Africa...

306
0:50:35,920 --> 0:50:38,320
冲浪海豚的家
..home to surfing dolphins.

307
0:50:43,880 --> 0:50:47,960
摄制组的任务是和冲浪海豚一道前行
The team's mission here is to ride alongside the dolphins

308
0:50:47,960 --> 0:50:52,400
以前所未有的细致记录下它们的冲浪行为
and record their surfing behaviour in closer detail than ever before.

309
0:50:56,440 --> 0:51:02,980
这些海域不可捉摸 所以摄制组请来了当地的冲浪专家做向导
These are treacherous seas so the film crew enlists local professional surfers to guide them.

310
0:51:11,720 --> 0:51:16,000
但今年 浪比任何人预想的都大
But this year, the waves are bigger than anyone had anticipated.

311
0:51:17,980 --> 0:51:21,680
这让冲浪摄影师克里斯·瑞恩感到很紧张
A daunting prospect for surf cameraman Chris Ryan.

312
0:51:23,520 --> 0:51:25,280
对 我感到很紧张
Yeah, I'm feeling pretty nervous...

313
0:51:26,680 --> 0:51:28,560
海面上有巨大的涌浪
It's a big swell out there.

314
0:51:28,560 --> 0:51:30,440
真的是很大的涌浪
Really big swell.

315
0:51:30,440 --> 0:51:33,880
浪足有20英尺高
There's 20ft waves out there and...

316
0:51:33,880 --> 0:51:37,280
对 这也许是我去过的最危险的海域
..yeah, this will probably be the biggest sea I've ever been out in.

317
0:51:37,280 --> 0:51:38,720
我想 没有付出 就没有回报
No risk, no reward, I guess.

318
0:51:41,240 --> 0:51:45,400
克里斯有一个高速摄像机能够拍到海浪中的
Chris has a high-speed camera to shoot super-slow-motion action

319
0:51:45,400 --> 0:51:46,840
超慢镜头
in the waves.

320
0:51:51,720 --> 0:51:53,560
挑战是要尽量接近
The challenge is to get as close

321
0:51:53,560 --> 0:51:55,800
冲浪的海豚
to the wave-riding dolphins as possible.

322
0:51:59,000 --> 0:52:02,640
好消息是我们在地平线上发现了海豚
The good news is that the dolphins have been spotted on the horizon.

323
0:52:08,600 --> 0:52:11,340
他们说这是今年最大的浪
They said this was going to be the biggest swell of the year

324
0:52:12,040 --> 0:52:14,120
我从没见过这种场面
hey, I've never seen anything like this.

325
0:52:14,120 --> 0:52:16,760
这浪比我想像的可大多了
This is much bigger than I had possibly imagined.

326
0:52:24,240 --> 0:52:29,400
在这种时候 只有摩托艇能接近海豚
In these waves, the only way to get out to the dolphins is with a jet ski.

327
0:52:31,280 --> 0:52:32,930
光是翻过那些巨浪
It's going to be enough of a challenge for them

328
0:52:32,940 --> 0:52:34,790
就已经够困难的了
just to kind of weave their way out.

329
0:52:59,000 --> 0:53:01,600
最终驾驶员精湛的技术
At last the driver's detailed knowledge

330
0:53:01,600 --> 0:53:04,440
带他们安全越过了巨浪
gets them safely through the massive breakers.

331
0:53:07,400 --> 0:53:09,280
但宽吻海豚不见了
But the dolphins are nowhere to be seen...

332
0:53:13,400 --> 0:53:16,440
摄制组只得返回岸上
..leaving the crew to face the hair-raising task

333
0:53:16,440 --> 0:53:17,880
但回来的路将会更惊险
of getting back to shore.

334
0:53:32,520 --> 0:53:34,440
快 快 快
Go, go, go, go!

335
0:53:43,840 --> 0:53:46,160
哦
Oh!

336
0:53:49,840 --> 0:53:52,120
看见了吗 太疯狂了
How was that? That was pretty wild, yeah.

337
0:53:52,540 --> 0:53:57,280
浪打到摩托艇的尾部 我不停地说 快点 快点 我们得赶快离开这
the wave actully hit the back of the sled and i was like go, go, get out of here, guys get out of here

338
0:53:57,280 --> 0:53:59,680
赶快离开 它一下子撞上来差点反弹出去
"get out of here." It hit a big bump but almost bounced off

339
0:53:59,680 --> 0:54:03,280
我一直紧紧抓住摄像机 一路冲回来 但是
I was trying to hold the camera and just rode out of there, but, yeah,

340
0:54:03,280 --> 0:54:05,320
这真是太疯狂了
it was hectic.

341
0:54:05,320 --> 0:54:07,010
又得回家剪片子了
Just another day at the office.

342
0:54:12,720 --> 0:54:16,320
第二天天气陡然好转
The next day brings a sudden change in conditions.

343
0:54:20,960 --> 0:54:23,400
有很多海豚
Plenty of dolphins

344
0:54:23,400 --> 0:54:24,880
海面却很平静
but a calmer sea.

345
0:54:26,080 --> 0:54:28,520
一点风浪都没有
A complete lack of any wave at all!

346
0:54:30,360 --> 0:54:32,480
它们会出现的 会出现的
They'll come, they'll come, they'll come!

347
0:54:36,040 --> 0:54:37,920
在海上
As so often in the ocean,

348
0:54:37,920 --> 0:54:41,520
通常只要在正确的位置 你只需耐心等候
if you know you're in the right place, you just need the patience

349
0:54:41,520 --> 0:54:43,360
时机的到来
to wait for the perfect moment.

350
0:54:51,080 --> 0:54:55,960
一周后 又一次风暴在狂野海岸酝酿着
A week later and the storm is once again brewing off the wild coast,

351
0:54:55,960 --> 0:54:58,000
海浪渐渐涌起
and surf is building.

352
0:54:58,000 --> 0:55:00,120
我感到很激动
I feel, like, a nervous excitement.

353
0:55:00,120 --> 0:55:02,480
拍摄的条件堪称完美
The conditions are absolutely perfect, this is

354
0:55:02,480 --> 0:55:05,680
完全是我们想要的效果
completely what we've been waiting for.

355
0:55:05,680 --> 0:55:07,480
海豚也好像知道（我们要拍它们）似的
And the dolphins seem to know it.

356
0:55:09,640 --> 0:55:13,000
但克里斯没法平稳地拍摄
But Chris is struggling to get a steady shot.

357
0:55:16,370 --> 0:55:17,520
那里怎么样
How about that?

358
0:55:18,680 --> 0:55:21,560
嗨 先生们 太难了
Hello, gentlemen. Tricky.

359
0:55:21,560 --> 0:55:24,390
在摩托艇上要找到合适的角度太难了
A little tricky on the jet ski just trying to get the right angle.

360
0:55:24,400 --> 0:55:26,450
所以这次我跟左迪亚克一起去
So I'm going to have a go with the Zodiac

361
0:55:26,450 --> 0:55:28,840
希望这次能成功
and hopefully have better luck on that one.

362
0:55:40,440 --> 0:55:43,280
橡皮艇给了克里斯一个更大
The inflatable boat gives Chris a larger,

363
0:55:43,280 --> 0:55:45,520
更平稳的摄影平台
more stable filming platform.

364
0:55:48,800 --> 0:55:53,000
终于 时机正好
At last, he is in exactly the right place at exactly the right time.

365
0:55:58,760 --> 0:56:00,680
结果堪称完美
And the results are spectacular.

366
0:56:12,320 --> 0:56:13,560
任务圆满成功
Mission accomplished.

367
0:56:20,880 --> 0:56:24,040
这些珍贵的影像
And this intimate footage is now available

368
0:56:24,040 --> 0:56:26,760
为科学研究提供了资料
as part of wider scientific studies.

369
0:56:30,260 --> 0:56:34,840
帮助证明海豚冲浪 是为了增进友谊 
Supporting evidence that dolphins surf to strengthen friendships,

370
0:56:34,880 --> 0:56:40,040
培养社交技能 以及获得快乐
develop social skills and for the sheer exhilaration of it.

371
0:56:51,000 --> 0:56:54,440
下一期 深海
Next time, the deep.

372
0:56:55,920 --> 0:57:00,120
一个比你想象中更丰富多彩的世界
A world richer than we ever thought possible,

373
0:57:00,120 --> 0:57:03,480
地球最极端环境中
where creatures thrive

374
0:57:03,480 --> 0:57:06,760
也有蓬勃的生机
in the most extreme conditions on Earth.

375
